### Code

```Rust
#[derive(Default)]
struct Node {
    value: i32,
    children: Vec<Node>,
}
fn main() {
    let values: Vec<i32> = vec![];
    let mut root: Node = Default::default();
    let mut current_node = &mut root;

    'outer: for value in values {
        for (i, element) in current_node.children.iter_mut().enumerate() {
            if element.value == value {
                // current_node = &mut current_node.children[i]; // This one works
                current_node = element; // This one doesn't
                continue 'outer;
            }
        }
    }
}
```


### Current output

```Shell
error[E0499]: cannot borrow `current_node.children` as mutable more than once at a time
  --> src/main.rs:12:29
   |
12 |         for (i, element) in current_node.children.iter_mut().enumerate() {
   |                             ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
   |                             |
   |                             `current_node.children` was mutably borrowed here in the previous iteration of the loop
   |                             first borrow used here, in later iteration of loop

For more information about this error, try `rustc --explain E0499`.
warning: `rust` (bin "rust") generated 1 warning
error: could not compile `rust` due to previous error; 1 warning emitted
```


### Desired output

```Shell
I'm really not sure what the output should be but I think it should somehow include the actual line that needs to be change if that's possible because before I figured out the problem I thought that line would have been "released" and hence couldn't understand why it was still pointing to the line with the for loop.
```


### Rationale and extra context

The problem is much easier to see in a more "full" example closer to the original code [here](https://github.com/c-git/leetcode/blob/e65a012aa993d1d686267bca697f6fd50877f74a/rust/src/_208_implement_trie_prefix_tree.rs).

As a beginner I didn't understand how long the variable was borrowed and hence couldn't easily figure out what was wrong. Eventually found it by just commenting out lines one at a time. The MRE from above is also available on in a repo [here](https://github.com/c-git/leetcode/blob/e65a012aa993d1d686267bca697f6fd50877f74a/rust/src/main.rs).

### Other cases

```Rust
#[derive(Default)]
struct Node {
    value: i32,
    children: Vec<Node>,
}
fn main() {
    let values: Vec<i32> = vec![];
    let mut root: Node = Default::default();
    let mut current_node = &mut root;

    'outer: for value in values {
        for (i, element) in current_node.children.iter_mut().enumerate() {
            if element.value == value {
                current_node = &mut current_node.children[i]; // This one works                
                continue 'outer;
            }
        }
    }
}
```


